<p>Although the legal age for marriage is 18 years old in Madagascar, child marriage is still allowed with the consent of the parents. Child marriage puts girls at serious health risks of premature pregnancy and of contracting STIs, as well as domestic violence and abuse. Just as with other slavery-like practices discussed in this section, poverty is a significant factor in the prevalence of these practices. In these extreme circumstances, women and children become particularly vulnerable as all types of “services” they can provide are exchanged for money.
</p>

<h4>Recommendations [12]</h4>

<ul>
  <li>The Government needs to reinforce the existing legal framework to eradicate the worst forms of child labor, and put in place effective monitoring mechanisms that identify children at risk or victims of these practices.
</li>
  <li>Programs should be established in local communities to address caste discrimination and the stigma experienced by descendents of the slave caste.
</li>
  <li>Ensuring free education and literacy programmes for children would help at-risk children remain in the education system. Free vocational training, backed up with employment opportunities, is also crucial in providing teenagers and adults with viable economic alternatives to slavery-like practices. 
</li>
  <li>Strict regulations should be established and implemented in the business sector preventing children from being exploited in mining and agricultural sectors.
</li>
  <li>Strengthen the legal framework protecting Malagasy domestic workers and put mechanisms in place overseeing that work conditions are up to standards and that workers are receiving fair treatment.
</li>
  <li>Enforcement of the laws against human trafficking need to be improved. Girl markets need to be shut down and government should enforce the obligation to register all marriages so as to monitor their compliance with the law.
</li>
  <li>Strong measures need to be taken to increase women’s access to all levels of education and health-care, including family planning options, particularly in rural areas.
</li>
</ul>
